WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:04.200
This motion graphics video is the perfect&nbsp;
example of how some simple effects can really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:08.040
improve a “basic” animation and help to sell&nbsp;
it as more interesting than what actually is.&nbsp;

00:00:08.040 --> 00:00:11.520
In this video I want to recreate some&nbsp;
oh these compositions and share with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:13.620
you some simple effects combinations that we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:17.160
add to any animation to create that&nbsp;
extra layer of care and attention..

00:00:19.740 --> 00:00:22.920
this video in sponsored by celwizard&nbsp;
frame by frame animation library,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:25.200
but more about that after the tutorial

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:28.140
the first effect is deform at impact.

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:33.060
I have a normal bouncing ball, but it’s not&nbsp;
really convincing. It's a little bit stiff,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:36.660
I could improve it with some squash&nbsp;
and stretch, but sometimes squash and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.660 --> 00:00:40.320
stretch can be a little too cartoony so&nbsp;
here's an alternative that you can try…

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:44.280
create an adjustment layer and&nbsp;
position it above the element that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.280 --> 00:00:50.160
is going to be deformed by the impact.
apply the effect “liquify” and select&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:54.840
the brush tool, adjust the dimension&nbsp;
and now you can distort your layer.

00:01:04.020 --> 00:01:08.700
Then add a keyframe to the distortion&nbsp;
percentage and set it at 100 at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:11.700
moment of the impact, set it&nbsp;
to zero at the frame before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:28.800
and zero again after more or&nbsp;
less half second after the impact

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:34.200
ok, now I want to smooth the curve&nbsp;
a little bit and I'm copying these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:37.860
keyframes for every bounce, where&nbsp;
I've put the keyframe in red.

00:01:52.380 --> 00:02:00.120
Since the sphere loses kinetic energy&nbsp;
at every bounce we have to lower the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:05.100
percentage of the distortion. I'm setting&nbsp;
the second bounce at 70 instead of 100,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:21.960
and the third bounce only at 20.

00:02:35.452 --> 00:02:37.380
reactive light and shadows..

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:42.120
this is a very popular one, maybe because it’s&nbsp;
really cool while also really easy to make..&nbsp;

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:46.200
I have this composition with my sphere&nbsp;
that moves around this grid of panels.&nbsp;

00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:50.040
the only animations at the moment&nbsp;
are just a few position keyframes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:53.520
on the sphere that move between the&nbsp;
panels.. and i also animated the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:56.579
position of the panels to make some&nbsp;
room when the sphere passes through.

00:02:56.579 --> 00:02:59.340
 the first thing to do is to duplicate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:04.920
the composition where you have all of your&nbsp;
environment and apply the effect RADIAL FAST BLUR

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:08.820
then you have to select the center of&nbsp;
the effect and position it on the sphere,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:15.660
then select the center property pickwhip&nbsp;
and parent it to the position of the sphere.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.660 --> 00:03:19.800
now the center of the radial fast blur&nbsp;
will follow the position of the sphere.

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:26.940
I want to increase the amount of radial&nbsp;
blur a little bit, let’say to 90.. and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:31.740
I also want to have it in a uniform color so&nbsp;
I'm applying a fill effect to make it blue..

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:45.180
we are done with the shadows, no&nbsp;
we need some dynamic light so we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:49.680
can duplicate our environment layer
apply a brightness effect on it.&nbsp;

00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:56.760
then we create a new solid layer and&nbsp;
use a mask to create a faded circle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:15.240
and we’ll use this circle as a matte&nbsp;
for the brighter environment comp.&nbsp;

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:20.160
Then if we parent our faded circle to your sphere,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:24.660
the matte will follow the sphere position and&nbsp;
that’s it. Now we have a light and shadow system&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:28.620
that follows your elements and create a really&nbsp;
cool interaction with the graphics around it.

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:37.147
last effect is revealing lenses

00:04:37.147 --> 00:04:37.410
I think it’s really cool&nbsp;
to show something through a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:38.460
sliding of something transparent, like a&nbsp;
sort of lens that shows a hidden layer.

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:42.000
First thing I recreated a similar comp to&nbsp;
my video reference but you can obviously&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:48.360
it in any different type of context.. I have some&nbsp;
concentric circles, one with a 4 gradient effect.&nbsp;

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:54.240
another circle, some graphics and an&nbsp;
adjustment layer with a blur effect,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:58.620
a brightness affect and some mask.
i have the usual blue sphere that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:03.900
rotate inside the circle and scale to the center.
and lastly parented to the sphere i have a comp

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:08.700
with an animation of floating object that will&nbsp;
be the hidden layer that is inside of the sphere.&nbsp;

00:05:08.700 --> 00:05:13.260
Now we have to set up our lenses&nbsp;
to reveal the hidden layer…

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:18.360
First of all we create a new adjustment layer,&nbsp;
and we apply a gaussian blur effect on it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:25.980
we create a circular mask and increase&nbsp;
the blur effect and we already can start&nbsp;&nbsp;to see that this is the right direction..

00:05:38.287 --> 00:05:45.960
In my case I want to create a round shape&nbsp;&nbsp;layer because I want a stroke around my lens,&nbsp;
so I'm parenting a round shape layer to my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:49.980
adjustment layer, but you can skip this part,&nbsp;
depending on the aesthetic of your project.

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:55.620
then we need to create a second circle for the&nbsp;
second lens and we need to have this new circle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.620 --> 00:06:04.080
cancel out the blur of the first one.
Like if by aligning the second lens it creates a focus and removes the blurriness of the first lens.

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:18.715
so we select the first circle and set the new one as a matte.

00:06:18.715 --> 00:06:22.215
after that we click on this icon to invert tha matte

00:06:22.215 --> 00:06:25.519
so that the blurriness of the first lens is only outside the second one

00:06:26.869 --> 00:06:33.070
ok perfect now we have a second circle that work as revealer, and where it moves cancels&nbsp;&nbsp;the blur effect

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:37.939
Now it’s time to play a little bit with the&nbsp;
position of our lenses,

00:06:37.939 --> 00:06:40.500
so in this case i’m&nbsp;&nbsp;moving the lens position to the side

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:45.060
I want to apply the same position&nbsp;
animation also to the first lens,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.060 --> 00:06:46.920
add some ease to smooth the movement.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:57.480
along with the position i also&nbsp;
want to animate the dimension

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:01.020
of the lenses so that they scale up&nbsp;
while moving toward the center

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:06.600
I also need to animate the stroke thickness to&nbsp;
keep it consistent during the scale but that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:11.580
only because I choose to add that stroke to&nbsp;
frame my lens and you can totally avoid that..

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:18.420
ok we animated the position and scale of the&nbsp;
lens going into the scene, now we can just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:23.640
copy the keyframe to make them going out.
I also want to add some rotation around the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:27.480
center so I'm going to add a Null object&nbsp;
that will be the center of the rotation..&nbsp;

00:07:27.693 --> 00:07:31.800
Then we can then parent our lenses&nbsp;
to this new null object and if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:35.700
keyframe the null rotation giving him a&nbsp;
couple of rounds the lenses will follow…

00:07:36.660 --> 00:07:39.660
to create a more dynamic scene we can also set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:42.900
some offset between the scale&nbsp;
and position of the two lenses.&nbsp;

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:46.800
we just need to select all the keyframes&nbsp;
from the first layer and move them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:52.020
slightly along the timeline.. I would say&nbsp;
something around just 5 or 10 frames..

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:01.560
i want to separate a little bit&nbsp;
the two layer so i’m adding a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:04.200
drop shadow effect and setting it very light

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:16.860
here you go three cool effect that you can try&nbsp;
when a client ask you for some “wow effect”

